      "content": "but \"trusting the process\" is exactly how this stuff gets away with it. if they wanted to hide a massive data extraction layer, they'd use exactly the excuses you're giving me—calling it a \"proprietary protocol\" or \"optimizing performance.\" if we look at how much control these kernel-level updates actually have, they could essentially turn the entire OS into a distributed sensor network without anyone ever noticing. if someone *was* trying to use hardware-level access to scrape biological or cognitive data, wouldn't that be the perfect way to do it under the guise of \"system stability\"?",
